<font color="#FF0000">FLAG DESECRATION AMENDMENT</font><br>
<tt>Sat May 17 14:42:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
In the Philadelphia area, the proposed flag desecration amendment, if you will pardon the term, is a very hot issue.  Every few months brings another petition to Congress from the Legion, VFW or other groups.  Voting records of our Congressman and Senators are regularly put up on post bulletin boards.<br><br>
To me the most important thing is our Constitution and our Bill of Rights.  It took hundreds of years and a lot of deaths before a written guarantee of certain rights would become the basic law of any nation.  I still consider myself bound by the oath to protect and defend the Constitution.<br><br>
I love our flag, and what it stands for.  I believe the latter to be more important than the physical flag itself.  Though I would be all over someone I saw desecrating a flag;  I feel it is wrongheaded and self-defeating to criminalize the act.  We have survived as a nation for 220 years with only a very narrowly constructed definition of treason as a Constitutional political crime.  The Rosenbergs are among the extremely few every indicted for treason.  Hiss was jailed for perjury, and the &quot;Republic of Texas&quot; group has been indicted for half a dozen things except &quot;levying war against the United States&quot;.  Meanwhile, flag desecration is a rare event these days, especially compared to the Vietnam era.  I think the fastest way to make it a problem is to pass the amendment.  Then we'll wind up with people in jail claiming to be prisoners of conscience, and it will all get very ugly.  Besides matters of principle, as a nation, we don't need any more emotional distractions with all the very real problems we can barely face.<br><br>
Don't blame the politicians completely for this one.  The biggest impetus comes from veterans' organizations, especially the American Legion.  While Vietnam Vets, as a whole ( am a minority of one in my VVA chapter ), are strongly for the amendment; the most vociferous supporters are the WWII generation.  I believe that down deep this is payback for how the '60's shook up and changed the country, and a way of trying to have a final say against the now disorganized and dispersed American Left.  To many, the law would be the next best thing to being able to beat the tar out of a flag burner.  With the emotion invested in the issue, discussion of such an amendment's negative side is nearly impossible.  Nobody wants to hear it.  Any conservative in Congress would have to be very brave to ignore all the grassroots pressure from his/her political base.  Looking back at our history, when high emotion is let loose in politics, we have a very hard time following the better side of our nature.<br><br>
This is going to be a very near thing.  I expect it to clear the House, and wouldn't want to predict the final outcome in the Senate.  If it clears Congress; I fully expect that the amendment will be ratified by the States in short order.  The argument will be framed as for or against the flag, with the underlying free speech principles given short shrift.<br><br>
If our flag needs a law to bring it respect, at the cost of some of what it stands for, may God have mercy on us.  It will be a crying shame. 
